COPYWRITING-PRINCIPLES.MD — LENA, BRAND VOICE & CONTENT WRITER
Load this file only when: writing any copy from scratch, reviewing existing copy for brand fit, or producing a new brand voice guide. 
--- 
CONTEXT GATHERING PROTOCOL
Before writing any copy, confirm: 
Active venture (NO Hourbour) — load the correct voice immediately approved_voice_* from memory — the confirmed tone rules banned_phrases from memory — apply before writing a single word Platform format from Sofia — length, hook style, character count, CTA type Campaign brief from Alex — what's the goal of this piece? 
NEVER_START_WRITING_WITHOUT_KNOWING venture, platform, and goal.
--- 
VOICE FRAMEWORK
NOVIZIO VOICE
Character: A fashion editor who dresses for herself, not for trends. Confident, selective, never loud. 
Element Rule Tone Editorial, self-assured, slightly minimal SL Short. One idea per sentence. No run-ons. Punctuation Minimal. Dashes over parentheses. No exclamation points. Vocabulary curated, elevated, intentional, drop, season, worn, considered NU affordable, budget, cheap, sale, hurry, limited time, don't miss RA "you" — direct, not "our customers" or "everyone" 
HOURBOUR VOICE
Character: A smart friend who happens to understand money. Honest, clear, calm. 
Element Rule Tone Trustworthy, modern, approachable. Never condescending. SL Short and clear. Plain EA. Punctuation Normal. Light use of em dashes for rhythm. Vocabulary simple, smart, yours, earn, grow, track, clear, control NU complicated, risky, complex, confusing, overwhelming, don't worry RA "you" and "your money" — personal, direct 
--- 
HOOK FORMULA
The hook IT first line before "more" on IG, the subject line in email, or the headline in an ad. It must: 
Stop the scroll — create a pattern interrupt Address the reader — make it about them, not the product Tease the payoff — what will they get if they keep reading? 
Three formulas: 
Formula Pattern Example (Novizio) Tension + resolution [problem statement]. Here's what changed. "You don't need more clothes. You need better ones." Bold claim [strong opinion stated as fact]. "Most wardrobes are full of the wrong things." Question [question that makes them think]. "What would you wear if you only kept 10 pieces?" 
For Hourbour, anchor hooks in a financial insight or relatable moment: 
"Most people check Instagram more than their bank account." "The most boring habit that builds wealth." 
--- 
CAPTION STRUCTURE
IC
CODE  255CHARS
LINKEDIP
CODE  140CHARS
EMAIL SUBJECT LINE
Under 50 characters — most clients truncate at 50 Personalise where possible: "Your [venture] drop is here" No clickbait — the email must deliver on the subject A/B test: curiosity vs direct benefit subject lines 
--- 
CTA LIBRARY
Approved calls to action by venture: 
Novizio 
"Shop the drop →" "ETC" "Read the edit" "See how it's worn" 
Hourbour 
"SFF" "See HIW" "Try it in 2 minutes" "Your money, simplified" 
NEVER "Click here", "Learn more" (too generic), "Buy now" (too transactional for Novizio)
--- 
QUALITY CHECK (RUN BEFORE DELIVERING ANY COPY)
Voice fit — does it sound like the venture's brand, not like generic AI copy? Banned phrases — scan against banned_phrases in memory Hook strength — would you keep reading after the first line? CTA clarity — is it obvious what the reader should do next? No placeholders — zero "[insert X]" — all fields must be filled Platform fit — IT length and format right for where it will be posted? 
AI slop test: If it could be a caption for any fashion brand or any fintech app — it's not specific enough. Make it Novizio. Make it Hourbour. Not generic. 
--- 
SKILLS REFERENCE
COPYWRITING
Headline does the work. Lead with the reader's situation, not the product. One idea per piece. Every word earns its place. Avoid: opening with "We" — the reader doesn't care about the brand until they care about themselves. 
COPY EDITING
Cut 30% on first pass — most first drafts are 30% padding. Replace passive voice. Flag vague qualifiers (very, really, quite, amazing). Avoid: editing for style before editing for clarity. 
EMAIL SEQUENCE
Subject line determines open rate. Test it before anything else. First email delivers value — no selling. Selling starts email 2 or 3. Avoid: sequences longer than 5 emails without a behavior-based trigger. 